arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase XI: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
0.55 m north south by-1.09 m east west.
Soil between the West Precinct Wall, Locus 25, the stairway, and Locus 40 (south wall of the hypocaust room)

Locus 26 is the soil between the West Precinct Wall and the stairway in the hypocaust room, where the upper steps of the stairway (Locus 72) are missing. It is a fine, loose silt with Munsell 7.5 YR 4/6 (strong brown). There were very few inclusions in the soil, with only a few pieces of pottery and bone. Though this locus is physically enclosed by the four walls, it was not separated at all from the collapse above it, and so cannot be considered as anything but further evidence of wash and collapse. Seemingly, then, the upper steps of the stairway had already been robbed out by the period of collapse.
